Ancient China (2100 BCE - 221 CE):
The Xia Dynasty is believed to be the first Chinese dynasty, established around 2100 BCE. The following dynasties include the Shang Dynasty (1600-1046 BCE), Zhou Dynasty (1046-256 BCE), Qin Dynasty (221-206 BCE), Han Dynasty (206 BCE-220 CE), and several other smaller dynasties. During this period, Chinese civilization developed and flourished, with advancements in agriculture, technology, and governance.

Imperial China (221-1912 CE):
After the fall of the Han Dynasty, China was divided into several warring states, which were eventually unified under the Jin Dynasty in 280 CE. The Sui Dynasty was established in 581 CE, marking the beginning of Imperial China. This period saw significant political, social, and economic changes, including the construction of the Grand Canal, the development of Buddhism, and the creation of the imperial examination system for selecting officials. The Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) and Qing Dynasty (1644-1912) are notable for their cultural achievements and territorial expansions.

Modern China (1912-present):
In 1912, the Republic of China was established, led by Sun Yat-sen. However, the country was plagued by warlordism, corruption, and foreign invasion, leading to the Communist Revolution in 1949. Mao Zedong established the People's Republic of China, which became a socialist state after 1949. Following Mao's death in 1976, China began its transformation into a market-based economy and opened up to global trade and investment. Today, China is the world's second-largest economy and a major player on the global stage.

